\f0\b\fs36 \cf3 Server
\f1\b0 \cf0   
\fs28 \cf3 SuperCollider\cf0  3 \cf3 Synth\cf0  \cf3 Server\cf0  is a simple but powerful synthesis engine. \cf3 While\cf0  synthesis is running, new modules can be created, destroyed and repatched, sample buffers can be created and reallocated. \cf3 Effects\cf0  processes can be created and patched into a signal flow dynamically at scheduled times.  \cf3 All\cf0  running modules are ordered in a tree of nodes that define an order of execution. \cf3 Patching\cf0  between modules is done through global audio and control buses. \
\
\cf3 All\cf0  commands are received via \cf3 TCP\cf0  or \cf3 UDP\cf0  using a simplified version of \cf3 Open\cf0  \cf3 Sound\cf0  \cf3 Control\cf0  (\cf3 OSC\cf0 ). \cf3 The\cf0  synth server and its client(s) may be on the same machine or across a network. \cf3 The\cf0  synth server does not send or receive \cf3 MIDI\cf0 . \cf3 It\cf0  is expected that the client will send all control commands. \cf3 If\cf0  \cf3 MIDI\cf0  is desired, it is up to the client to receive it and convert it to appropriate \cf3 OSC\cf0  commands for the synth engine.\
\
\cf3 Synth\cf0  definitions are stored in files generated by the \cf3 SuperCollider\cf0  language application. \cf3 Unit\cf0  generator definitions are \cf3 Mach\cf0 -\cf3 O\cf0  bundles (not to be confused with \cf3 CFBundles\cf0 ). \cf3 The\cf0  \cf3 Unit\cf0  generator \cf3 API\cf0  is a simple \cf3 C\cf0  interface.\
	\
